mit. XXIX. After describing how obligations may arise from contract and quasi-contract, Justinian proceeds to show how they are discharged. Here the metaphor by which their creation is so vividly presented is consistently continued z an obligation is dissolved by the untying of the knot by the tying of which it was imposed, the general term employed being solvere, in the sense of loosing or releasing: ‘solvisse accipere debemus non tantum eum, qui solvit, verum omnem omnino qui ea obligatione liberatus est, quae ex causa iudicati descendit ’ Dig. 42. 1. 4. 7, ‘solvere dicimus eum, qui id facit quod facere promisit' Dig. 50. 16. 1'76, ‘solutionis verbum pertinet ad omnem liberationem quoquo modo factam, magisque ad substantiam obligationis refertur quam ad nummorum solutionem' Dig. ib. 47.
